# HTTP Methods, Status Codes, and Content Negotiation

## Introduction

HTTP is the foundation of every web API. While Express abstracts many details, understanding HTTP methods, status codes, headers, and content negotiation deeply is what separates a competent API developer from one who just "makes things work." This lesson covers the full spectrum of HTTP semantics you need for production API development.

## HTTP Methods in Depth

### GET — Retrieve Resources

```typescript
// Safe (no side effects) and idempotent
// MUST NOT have a request body (per HTTP spec)
router.get('/api/users', async (req, res) => {
  const users = await userService.findAll();
  res.json({ data: users });
});

// Conditional GET with ETag
router.get('/api/users/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await userService.findById(req.params.id);
  if (!user) return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });

  const etag = generateETag(user);
  if (req.get('If-None-Match') === etag) {
    return res.status(304).send(); // Not Modified
  }

  res.set('ETag', etag);
  res.json({ data: user });
});
```

### POST — Create Resources

```typescript
// NOT idempotent — calling twice creates two resources
router.post('/api/users', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await userService.create(req.body);

  // Return 201 Created with the new resource
  res.status(201)
     .set('Location', `/api/users/${user.id}`) // Location header
     .json({ data: user });
});
```

### PUT — Replace Resources

```typescript
// Idempotent — same request always produces same result
// Requires the COMPLETE resource representation
router.put('/api/users/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const { name, email, role } = req.body;

  // Validate all required fields are present
  if (!name || !email || !role) {
    return res.status(400).json({
      error: 'PUT requires all fields: name, email, role'
    });
  }

  const user = await userService.replace(req.params.id, { name, email, role });

  if (!user) {
    // PUT can create if resource does not exist (upsert)
    const newUser = await userService.create({ id: req.params.id, name, email, role });
    return res.status(201).json({ data: newUser });
  }

  res.json({ data: user }); // 200 OK
});
```

### PATCH — Partial Update

```typescript
// NOT guaranteed idempotent
router.patch('/api/users/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await userService.findById(req.params.id);
  if (!user) return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });

  // Only update provided fields
  const updated = await userService.update(req.params.id, req.body);
  res.json({ data: updated });
});
```

### DELETE — Remove Resources

```typescript
// Idempotent — deleting an already-deleted resource is fine
router.delete('/api/users/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const deleted = await userService.delete(req.params.id);

  if (!deleted) {
    // Two common approaches:
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });
    // OR: return 204 (idempotent — end state is the same)
  }

  res.status(204).send(); // No Content
});
```

### HEAD — Metadata Only

```typescript
// Same as GET but without the response body
// Express handles HEAD automatically for GET routes
// Useful for checking if a resource exists or getting headers
router.head('/api/users/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const exists = await userService.exists(req.params.id);
  res.status(exists ? 200 : 404).send();
});
```

### OPTIONS — Describe Capabilities

```typescript
// Usually handled by CORS middleware
// Can provide custom capability info
router.options('/api/users', (req, res) => {
  res.set('Allow', 'GET, POST, OPTIONS');
  res.status(204).send();
});
```

## HTTP Status Codes

### 2xx — Success

```typescript
200 OK              // Default success. GET, PUT, PATCH
201 Created         // Resource created. POST (include Location header)
202 Accepted        // Request accepted but processing not complete (async)
204 No Content      // Success with no body. DELETE, PUT with no response body
```

### 3xx — Redirection

```typescript
301 Moved Permanently    // Resource permanently moved (cacheable)
302 Found                // Temporary redirect
304 Not Modified         // Conditional GET — client cache is still valid
307 Temporary Redirect   // Same as 302 but preserves HTTP method
308 Permanent Redirect   // Same as 301 but preserves HTTP method
```

### 4xx — Client Errors

```typescript
400 Bad Request          // Malformed request, validation error
401 Unauthorized         // No authentication or invalid credentials
403 Forbidden            // Authenticated but not authorized
404 Not Found            // Resource does not exist
405 Method Not Allowed   // HTTP method not supported for this route
409 Conflict             // Conflicts with current state (duplicate, version mismatch)
410 Gone                 // Resource permanently removed (unlike 404, won't return)
415 Unsupported Media Type // Wrong Content-Type header
422 Unprocessable Entity // Syntactically valid but semantically invalid
429 Too Many Requests    // Rate limit exceeded
```

### 5xx — Server Errors

```typescript
500 Internal Server Error  // Unexpected server error
502 Bad Gateway            // Invalid response from upstream server
503 Service Unavailable    // Server overloaded or in maintenance
504 Gateway Timeout        // Upstream server did not respond in time
```

### Choosing the Right Status Code

```
Decision tree for common scenarios:

Request succeeded?
  Yes -> Did it create something?
           Yes -> 201 Created
           No  -> Is there a response body?
                    Yes -> 200 OK
                    No  -> 204 No Content
  No  -> Is it the client's fault?
           Yes -> Is the request malformed?
                    Yes -> 400 Bad Request
                    No  -> Is it an auth problem?
                             Not logged in -> 401 Unauthorized
                             No permission -> 403 Forbidden
                             Not found     -> 404 Not Found
                             Duplicate     -> 409 Conflict
                             Validation    -> 422 Unprocessable Entity
           No  -> 500 Internal Server Error
```

## Content Negotiation

Content negotiation lets clients and servers agree on the response format:

### Accept Header

```typescript
router.get('/api/users/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await userService.findById(req.params.id);
  if (!user) return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });

  res.format({
    'application/json': () => {
      res.json({ data: user });
    },
    'text/csv': () => {
      res.set('Content-Type', 'text/csv');
      res.send(`id,name,email\n${user.id},${user.name},${user.email}`);
    },
    default: () => {
      res.status(406).json({ error: 'Not Acceptable' });
    }
  });
});
```

### Content-Type Header

The client tells the server what format the request body is in:

```typescript
// Handle different request content types
app.use(express.json());                          // application/json
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));  // application/x-www-form-urlencoded
app.use(express.text());                          // text/plain

router.post('/api/data', (req, res) => {
  if (req.is('json')) {
    // Handle JSON body
  } else if (req.is('urlencoded')) {
    // Handle form body
  } else {
    res.status(415).json({ error: 'Unsupported Media Type' });
  }
});
```

## Caching Headers

```typescript
// Cache-Control
router.get('/api/products', async (req, res) => {
  const products = await productService.findAll();

  res.set('Cache-Control', 'public, max-age=300'); // Cache for 5 min
  res.json({ data: products });
});

// No caching for dynamic/private data
router.get('/api/profile', auth, async (req, res) => {
  res.set('Cache-Control', 'private, no-cache');
  res.json({ data: req.user });
});

// ETag for conditional requests
router.get('/api/products/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const product = await productService.findById(req.params.id);
  const etag = `"${product.updatedAt.getTime()}"`;

  res.set('ETag', etag);

  if (req.get('If-None-Match') === etag) {
    return res.status(304).send();
  }

  res.json({ data: product });
});
```

## Common Headers for APIs

```typescript
// Standard response headers for APIs
function apiHeaders(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) {
  // Pagination info
  // res.set('X-Total-Count', totalCount.toString());
  // res.set('X-Page', page.toString());

  // Rate limiting info
  // res.set('X-RateLimit-Limit', '100');
  // res.set('X-RateLimit-Remaining', '95');
  // res.set('X-RateLimit-Reset', '1609459200');

  // Request tracking
  res.set('X-Request-Id', req.requestId || crypto.randomUUID());

  next();
}
```

## Common Pitfalls

### Using 200 for Everything

```typescript
// WRONG: always returning 200
res.status(200).json({ error: 'User not found' }); // Should be 404
res.status(200).json({ error: 'Validation failed' }); // Should be 400/422

// CORRECT: use appropriate status codes
res.status(404).json({ error: 'User not found' });
res.status(422).json({ error: 'Validation failed', details: [...] });
```

### 401 vs 403

```typescript
// 401 Unauthorized: "Who are you?" (no/invalid credentials)
// 403 Forbidden: "I know who you are, but you can't do this"

// No token provided or token is invalid
res.status(401).json({ error: 'Authentication required' });

// Valid token but user lacks permission
res.status(403).json({ error: 'Admin access required' });
```

## Summary

HTTP methods define operations (GET=read, POST=create, PUT=replace, PATCH=update, DELETE=remove). Status codes communicate outcomes precisely (2xx success, 4xx client error, 5xx server error). Content negotiation lets clients and servers agree on data formats. Use these semantics correctly and your API becomes self-documenting and predictable.

3.3.3.body:
# Standardized Error Responses and Validation

## Introduction

Inconsistent error responses are one of the most common complaints about APIs. When every endpoint returns errors in a different format, clients cannot reliably parse failures. This lesson covers standardized error response formats, input validation strategies using Zod and express-validator, and how to build a validation pipeline that produces clear, actionable error messages.

## The Problem with Inconsistent Errors

```typescript
// Inconsistent error formats across endpoints:
{ "error": "Not found" }
{ "message": "Invalid email", "code": 400 }
{ "errors": ["Name required", "Email invalid"] }
{ "status": "error", "reason": "Unauthorized" }

// Clients need special handling for each endpoint!
```

## Designing a Standard Error Format

### Simple Format

```typescript
interface ApiErrorResponse {
  success: false;
  error: {
    message: string;
    statusCode: number;
    code?: string;           // Machine-readable error code
    details?: unknown;        // Validation errors, etc.
  };
}
```

### RFC 7807 Problem Details (Industry Standard)

```typescript
interface ProblemDetails {
  type: string;       // URI identifying the error type
  title: string;      // Short human-readable summary
  status: number;     // HTTP status code
  detail?: string;    // Human-readable explanation
  instance?: string;  // URI identifying this occurrence
  [key: string]: any; // Extension fields
}

// Example response:
{
  "type": "https://api.example.com/errors/validation",
  "title": "Validation Error",
  "status": 422,
  "detail": "The request body contains invalid fields",
  "instance": "/api/users",
  "errors": [
    { "field": "email", "message": "Must be a valid email address" },
    { "field": "name", "message": "Must be between 2 and 100 characters" }
  ]
}
```

## Implementing Standardized Error Responses

```typescript
// src/utils/ApiError.ts
export class ApiError extends Error {
  constructor(
    public statusCode: number,
    message: string,
    public code?: string,
    public details?: unknown
  ) {
    super(message);
    this.name = 'ApiError';
  }

  toJSON(): object {
    return {
      success: false,
      error: {
        message: this.message,
        statusCode: this.statusCode,
        ...(this.code && { code: this.code }),
        ...(this.details && { details: this.details }),
      }
    };
  }
}

// src/middleware/errorHandler.ts
export function errorHandler(err: Error, req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) {
  if (err instanceof ApiError) {
    return res.status(err.statusCode).json(err.toJSON());
  }

  // Zod validation errors
  if (err.name === 'ZodError') {
    return res.status(422).json({
      success: false,
      error: {
        message: 'Validation failed',
        statusCode: 422,
        code: 'VALIDATION_ERROR',
        details: (err as any).errors,
      }
    });
  }

  // Default
  console.error('Unexpected error:', err);
  res.status(500).json({
    success: false,
    error: {
      message: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'
        ? 'Internal server error'
        : err.message,
      statusCode: 500,
      code: 'INTERNAL_ERROR',
    }
  });
}
```

## Input Validation with Zod

Zod is a TypeScript-first schema validation library that provides both validation and type inference:

```bash
npm install zod
```

### Creating Validation Schemas

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

// User creation schema
const createUserSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string()
    .min(2, 'Name must be at least 2 characters')
    .max(100, 'Name must be at most 100 characters')
    .trim(),
  email: z.string()
    .email('Must be a valid email address')
    .toLowerCase(),
  password: z.string()
    .min(8, 'Password must be at least 8 characters')
    .regex(/[A-Z]/, 'Password must contain at least one uppercase letter')
    .regex(/[0-9]/, 'Password must contain at least one number'),
  role: z.enum(['user', 'admin', 'editor']).default('user'),
  age: z.number().int().min(13).max(150).optional(),
  website: z.string().url().optional(),
});

// TypeScript type is inferred automatically
type CreateUserInput = z.infer<typeof createUserSchema>;
// { name: string; email: string; password: string; role: 'user' | 'admin' | 'editor'; age?: number; website?: string; }

// Update schema (all fields optional)
const updateUserSchema = createUserSchema.partial().omit({ password: true });

// Query parameters schema
const listUsersQuerySchema = z.object({
  page: z.string().transform(Number).pipe(z.number().int().min(1)).default('1'),
  limit: z.string().transform(Number).pipe(z.number().int().min(1).max(100)).default('20'),
  sort: z.enum(['name', 'email', 'createdAt']).default('createdAt'),
  order: z.enum(['asc', 'desc']).default('desc'),
  search: z.string().optional(),
  role: z.enum(['user', 'admin', 'editor']).optional(),
});
```

### Validation Middleware

```typescript
// src/middleware/validate.ts
import { z, ZodSchema, ZodError } from 'zod';

interface ValidationSchemas {
  body?: ZodSchema;
  query?: ZodSchema;
  params?: ZodSchema;
}

export function validate(schemas: ValidationSchemas) {
  return (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
    const errors: Array<{ location: string; field: string; message: string }> = [];

    for (const [location, schema] of Object.entries(schemas)) {
      if (!schema) continue;

      const data = (req as any)[location];
      const result = schema.safeParse(data);

      if (!result.success) {
        for (const issue of result.error.issues) {
          errors.push({
            location,
            field: issue.path.join('.'),
            message: issue.message,
          });
        }
      } else {
        // Replace with parsed/transformed data
        (req as any)[location] = result.data;
      }
    }

    if (errors.length > 0) {
      return res.status(422).json({
        success: false,
        error: {
          message: 'Validation failed',
          statusCode: 422,
          code: 'VALIDATION_ERROR',
          details: errors,
        }
      });
    }

    next();
  };
}
```

### Using Validation in Routes

```typescript
import { validate } from '../middleware/validate';
import { createUserSchema, updateUserSchema, listUsersQuerySchema } from './users.schemas';

const router = Router();

router.get('/',
  validate({ query: listUsersQuerySchema }),
  async (req, res) => {
    // req.query is now validated and typed
    const { page, limit, sort, order, search, role } = req.query;
    const users = await userService.findAll({ page, limit, sort, order, search, role });
    res.json({ success: true, data: users });
  }
);

router.post('/',
  validate({ body: createUserSchema }),
  async (req, res) => {
    // req.body is validated, trimmed, lowercased
    const user = await userService.create(req.body);
    res.status(201).json({ success: true, data: user });
  }
);

router.patch('/:id',
  validate({
    params: z.object({ id: z.string().regex(/^\d+$/, 'ID must be numeric') }),
    body: updateUserSchema,
  }),
  async (req, res) => {
    const user = await userService.update(req.params.id, req.body);
    res.json({ success: true, data: user });
  }
);
```

## Complex Validation Patterns

### Cross-Field Validation

```typescript
const dateRangeSchema = z.object({
  startDate: z.string().datetime(),
  endDate: z.string().datetime(),
}).refine(
  data => new Date(data.startDate) < new Date(data.endDate),
  { message: 'End date must be after start date', path: ['endDate'] }
);

const passwordChangeSchema = z.object({
  currentPassword: z.string(),
  newPassword: z.string().min(8),
  confirmPassword: z.string(),
}).refine(
  data => data.newPassword === data.confirmPassword,
  { message: 'Passwords do not match', path: ['confirmPassword'] }
).refine(
  data => data.currentPassword !== data.newPassword,
  { message: 'New password must be different', path: ['newPassword'] }
);
```

### Discriminated Unions

```typescript
const notificationSchema = z.discriminatedUnion('type', [
  z.object({
    type: z.literal('email'),
    email: z.string().email(),
    subject: z.string(),
  }),
  z.object({
    type: z.literal('sms'),
    phone: z.string().regex(/^\+\d{10,15}$/),
    message: z.string().max(160),
  }),
  z.object({
    type: z.literal('push'),
    deviceToken: z.string(),
    title: z.string(),
  }),
]);
```

## Error Response Examples

```json
// 400 Bad Request (malformed JSON)
{
  "success": false,
  "error": {
    "message": "Invalid JSON in request body",
    "statusCode": 400,
    "code": "INVALID_JSON"
  }
}

// 422 Validation Error
{
  "success": false,
  "error": {
    "message": "Validation failed",
    "statusCode": 422,
    "code": "VALIDATION_ERROR",
    "details": [
      { "location": "body", "field": "email", "message": "Must be a valid email address" },
      { "location": "body", "field": "password", "message": "Must be at least 8 characters" }
    ]
  }
}

// 404 Not Found
{
  "success": false,
  "error": {
    "message": "User with ID 999 not found",
    "statusCode": 404,
    "code": "RESOURCE_NOT_FOUND"
  }
}

// 409 Conflict
{
  "success": false,
  "error": {
    "message": "A user with this email already exists",
    "statusCode": 409,
    "code": "DUPLICATE_RESOURCE"
  }
}
```

## Common Pitfalls

### Validating Only the Request Body

```typescript
// WRONG: only validating body
router.get('/users', validate({ body: schema }), handler);

// CORRECT: validate query params for GET, params for route params
router.get('/users', validate({ query: listSchema }), handler);
router.get('/users/:id', validate({ params: idSchema }), handler);
router.post('/users', validate({ body: createSchema }), handler);
```

### Exposing Internal Error Details

```typescript
// WRONG: leaks Prisma error details
catch (err) {
  res.status(500).json({ error: err.message });
  // "Unique constraint failed on the fields: (`email`)"
}

// CORRECT: translate to user-friendly message
catch (err) {
  if (err.code === 'P2002') { // Prisma unique constraint
    throw new ApiError(409, 'A user with this email already exists', 'DUPLICATE_EMAIL');
  }
  throw err;
}
```

## Summary

Standardized error responses and robust input validation are non-negotiable for production APIs. Adopt a consistent error format (ideally RFC 7807), validate all input with Zod schemas, create reusable validation middleware, and translate internal errors to user-friendly messages. This makes your API predictable for clients and secure against malicious input.

